Now I understand the issue! Let me analyze the problem:

1. The failing test `discardsSpuriousByteOrderMarkWhenNoCharsetSet` expects a BOM (Byte Order Mark) to be handled properly when no charset is explicitly set.
2. Looking at the `parseByteData` method in DataUtil.java, I can see the issue.

The problem is in the order of operations in the `parseByteData` method. Here's what's happening:

1. When `charsetName` is `null`, the code first decodes the byte buffer using the default charset (UTF-8) and stores it in `docData`
2. Then it looks for meta tags to determine the charset
3. Finally, it checks for the BOM at the beginning of `docData` and if found, it re-decodes using UTF-8 and removes the BOM character

The issue is that the BOM check happens AFTER the charset detection from meta tags, but the BOM check should take precedence over everything else according to the comment: `// UTF-8 BOM indicator. takes precedence over everything else.`

However, the BOM check is only happening when `doc` is null, but when no charset is set, `doc` gets set during the initial parsing step, so the BOM check gets skipped in some cases.

Let me look more closely at the code flow to understand exactly what's happening:

```java
static Document parseByteData(ByteBuffer byteData, String charsetName, String baseUri, Parser parser) {
    String docData;
    Document doc = null;
    if (charsetName == null) { // determine from meta. safe parse as UTF-8
        // look for <meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html;charset=gb2312"> or HTML5 <meta charset="gb2312">
        docData = Charset.forName(defaultCharset).decode(byteData).toString();  // BOM is now part of docData
        doc = parser.parseInput(docData, baseUri);  // Document is created here with BOM still potentially in content
        Element meta = doc.select("meta[http-equiv=content-type], meta[charset]").first();
        if (meta != null) { // if not found, will keep utf-8 as best attempt
            // ... meta charset processing ...
        }
    } else { // specified by content type header (or by user on file load)
        Validate.notEmpty(charsetName, "Must set charset arg to character set of file to parse. Set to null to attempt to detect from HTML");
        docData = Charset.forName(charsetName).decode(byteData).toString();
    }
    // UTF-8 BOM indicator. takes precedence over everything else. rarely used. re-decodes incase above decoded incorrectly
    if (docData.length() > 0 && docData.charAt(0) == 65279) {  // BOM check happens here
        byteData.rewind();
        docData = Charset.forName(defaultCharset).decode(byteData).toString();
        docData = docData.substring(1);  // Remove BOM
        charsetName = defaultCharset;
    }
    if (doc == null) { // This condition is false when charsetName is null, because doc was already set above
        doc = parser.parseInput(docData, baseUri);
        doc.outputSettings().charset(charsetName);
    }
    return doc;
}
```

The issue is that when `charsetName` is `null`, the document `doc` is created BEFORE the BOM check, so the final `if (doc == null)` condition is false. This means the document is not re-parsed after the BOM is removed from `docData`, so the BOM remains in the document content.

